\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\sl259\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3953493 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3953493 The Little Known Islands That Lie Off Our Coast
\par 
\par By Waldo Drake
\par 
\par NEARLY 400 years ago Juan Rodriguez Cabrillo found these Isles of Summer, anchored in the
 azure sweep of the warm channel that flanks California's coast south from Point Concepcion. From Los Coronados north to the wind-swept San Miguel there are eleven islands; their shores bathed by the warm waters of the Japanese current, or Kuro Shiwo, and
 their sombre peaks and verdant valleys tempered by the fresh Westerly and the California sun.
\par 
\par From these and other weather factors they gain a climate that is hard to equal, having the life of the Mediterranean's Cote d'Azur without its chill winds and th
e tropic beauty of Madeira without its heat. Actually, they are the tops of mountains rising out of the sea, transformed from barren peaks by a combination of meteorological conditions into gardens of rare beauty and charm. For every man Who loves the out
doors the Channel Islands have their fascination.
\par 
\par Their blue and crystal-clear waters are the home of that bucking bronco of the sea, the leaping tuna, and all of his swaggering cousins, the albacore, the yellowtail, the bonito. Anglers come from all over 
the world to try their skill against these grand fighters, as well as the marlin and broadbill swordfish, the white sea bass, the blanquillo and a host of smaller game fishes.
\par 
\par They are the yachtsman's paradise, for it is hard to think of another place on 
earth where a sailor could find such perfect cruising grounds, with summer weather and fair winds the year around and scores of beautifUl little harbors where the yacht on leisurely cruise may anchor in safety. As for the thrill of cruising races, ask any
 Southland yachtsman who has fought his way down the west shore of San Clemente during a njght of contrary currents and constantly shifting breezes, finally to round Pyramid Head and then go boiling home to San Pedro under press of the westerly.
\par 
\par They have 
equal thrill for the hunter who has clambered rough canyons and over the needle crags of San Clemente in search of wild goats, or for his brother who in the dead of night has crawled for two miles on his belly to stalk the elusive white geese feeding on t
h
e tableland on Santa Rosa. Those lucky Nimrods who have hunted wild boars on Santa Cruz and Santa Rosa have enjoyed real danger and excitement and the man who likes upland game bird shooting can find his fill of doves and quail in the verdant slopes and w
ooded canyons of Santa Cruz.
\par 
\par The eleven Channel Islands are divided into three distinct groups. Northernmost are the santa Barbara group, lying about twenty miles offshore and ranging in an east-west line from Point Hueneme to Point Concepcion. They includ
e Anacapa, Santa Cruz, Santa Rosa and San Miguel. To the southward and off Point Vicente is the Santa Catalina group, including Santa Catalina, San Clemente, Santa Barbara and San Nicolas. Some ten miles south of Point Loma, off San Diego, are the three b
lack Los Coronados, called Las Islas Desiertas by Cabrillo.
\par 
\par Catalina needs no introduction. Last year more than 700,000 persons visited the Magic Isle via steamers of the Wrigley fleet alone, in addition to the thousands who traveled to Avalon, the isthmus
, Catalina Harbor and the island's myriad beauty spots aboard yachts. Catalina is needed, though, as a starting point for the early history of the Channel Islands, for on October 7, 1542, Cabrillo came ashore to visit an Indian village, variously located 
b
etween Avalon and the isthmus. He named the Island San Salvador for his flagship and San Clemente was called La Victoria, after Cabrllo's other vessel. But when Vizcaino visited the California coast in 1602 he gave the islands their present names, as well
 as changing the names of practically all of the other islands, bays and important headlands Cabrillo had discovered sixty years before.
\par 
\par In Cabrillo's Time
\par 
\par In Cabrillo's time all of the eight upper Channel Islands except Santa Barbara were peopled with In
dian tribes living in varying states of barbaric civilization. Pimugna was the native name for Santa Catalina. Authorities agree that the Pimugnans and the natives of San Clemente, called Kinkapar, spoke a dialect called Netela, but among all of the other
 islanders there were such wide differences in language that those living on neighboring islands in sight of each other could not understand one another.
\par 
\par {\*\atrfstart 419668171}Vizcaino and Torquemada both declared the islanders to be physiCally and mentally superior to the Indi
ans of the mainland and expressed admiration of their ability in building canoes and the dexterity with which they handled these craft, as well as their use of steatite for making mortars. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15466822 
{\*\atrfend 419668171}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 419668171}{\*\atndate 1730671446}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15466822 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15466822 Noble savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3953493 These mortars, made at the steatite quarries at Empire Landing, the Pimugnans are believed to have taken across channel to San Pedro Bay and sold to the mainland natives as the real beginning of the port's sea-borne trade.

\par 
\par Exceripts from the diary of the Costanso expedition, which came up the California coast in 1769, 227 years after Cabrillo, indicates that the Indians were still thriving on the Channel Islands:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\sl259\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid15466822 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3953493 {\*\atrfstart 419668172}
"They are of good figure and aspect, men and women; very much given to painting and staining with red ochre their faces 
and bodies. They use great headdresses of feathers, and some banderillas which they bind up amid their hair, with various trinkets and beads of coral of various colors. . . . The men work handsome trays of wood, with firm inlays or coral or of bone; and s
ome vases of much capacity, cloSing at the mouth, which appear to be made with a lathe(--)and with this machine they would not come out better-hollowed nor of more perfect form.
\par 
\par "In their houses, the married couples have their separate beds on platforms elevated from the ground. Their mattresses are some simple petates or mats of rushes, and their pillows are of the same petates rolled up at the head. All of these beds are hung a
bout with like mats, which serve for decency and protect from the cold.
\par 
\par "The dexterity and skill of these Indians is surpassing in the construction of their launches made of pine planking. They are from twenty-two to twentY-seven and one-half feet in lengt
h, including their rake, and of four feet beam . . . They handle the boats With equal cleverness, and three or four men go out to the open sea to fish in them, as they have capacity to carry eight or ten. They use long oars with two blades, and row With u
nspeakable lightness and velocity.
\par 
\par "They know all the arts of fishing, and fish abound along their coasts, as has been said of San Diego."}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15466822 {\*\atrfend 419668172}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn 
{\*\annotation{\*\atnref 419668172}{\*\atndate 1730671447}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15466822 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15466822 Noble savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3953493 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\sl259\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3953493 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3953493 
\par Life on the Channel Islands was for these savages a paradise. The waters abo
unded then, as now, in marine life of every form, fish, seals, whales, sharks, crayfish, abalones, mussels. Vast heaps of these shells and skeletons still found at town sites attest to the fact that these Indians were expert fishermen.
