\par "To me a more plausible explanation of the disappearance of the natives is that the Mission Fathers induced them to giv
e up their island life and settle about the missions, to be within easy reach of their teachings; and while many were killed in war, swept away by disease or by the invaders, doubtless the majority went to the various missions, where they soon lost their 
identity."
\par 
\par A Fragment of a Volcano
\par 
\par San Clemente Island, lying some twenty miles southwest of Catalina, is the weird fragment of some huge ancient volcano and its eighteen miles of lava flows, cactus-filled canyons, coast line caves and Vast sand dunes pre
sent a remarkable spectacle of desolatlOn, as compared to the grassy grazing plains of the middle island. Its windward cOast is largely low and flat, with several bays and anchorages, but the eastern shore(--)apparently the inner rim of a giant volcano(--
)presents nothing but towering cliffs of lava, in such grewsome, desolate expanse that one recal1s the illustrations of Dante's Inferno.
\par 
\par The island is owned by the United States government and has long been inhabited by herders on the sheep ranch operated 
by E. G. Blair, and several coves shelter shacks of fishermen. Its highest peak rises to only 1960 feet, yet a great portion of it is so mountainous that it affords ideal country for the thousands of wild goats still hunted [t]here about its needle-like l
ava crags and abysmal canyons.
\par 
\par San Clemente offers a fair example of the unusual bird life of all the Channel Islands. Its crags are the home of the American bald eagle and on the broad plains of the middle island are round valley quail, the mourning dove,
 humming birds, the savanna sparrow, rock wren, the house finch, lark, pewee, the California shrike and most of the coast's warblers. Ravens abound on San Clemente and about its sea-torn cliffs live the American osprey, the white-throated swift and the be
l
ted kingfisher. Sea birds making the various islands their winter home include the royal tern, the black-footed albatross, pelcans,cormorants, grebes, loons and auklets and the many species of shore waders. At certain seasons ducks and geese are found abo
ut the more verdant islands of Santa Rosa and Santa Cruz.
\par 
\par Santa Barbara and San Nicolas, the other two islands of the Santa Catalina group, are both United States government reservations. Santa Barbara's twin peaks rise out of the channel forty-s
even miles southwest of San Pedro, while bleak San Nicolas is some thirty farther offshore on almost the same bearing. A light has been estabilshed on little Santa Barbara, but it is uninhabited, save for large rookeries of cormorants, guillemots, pelican
s, auklets and the upland birds of the other islands. Almost surrounded by huge kelp beds, Santa Barbara Island waters are fine fishing grounds but they are little frequented by amateur anglers because of the island's isolated position.
\par 
\par San Nicolas Island,
 inhabited only by the lonely herders tending the sheep kept there by Messrs. Edward Vail and R. L. Brooks, is the most desolate, wind-swept waste of the entire Channel group, but in its story there lies the strange tale of the "Lost woman of san Nicolas.
"
\par 
\par In 1830 a schooner was sent to the island by the Mission Fathers to take off the last remnants of the dying tribe of Indians that had once thrived on San Nicolas. It was the Better Than Nothing, from San Pedro, and Capt. Sparks and his crew had taken abo
ard the last of the natives(--)numbering about a dozen(--)when one woman begged to be put ashore, explaining that she had left her child behind. She went ashore, ran up the beach, found her baby and hurried back to the schooner, onlY to find that the Bett
er Than Nothing was under way and heading offshore. Some versions of the tale indicate that the weather was so boisterous that Capt. Sparks was forced to put to sea. Others say that he deliberately left her.
\par 
\par At any rate, the schooner never returned and the
 woman's isolation became a matter of years. Finally, after twenty years, some otter hunter located her rude hut on the island, and reported it to the padres of the Mission Santa Barbara. Padre Gonzales dispatched Capt. Nidever to the island in search of 
her. On two trips he combed San Nicolas from end to end without success and on the third trip he took along a number of Indians and several santa Barbara residents, including one Charles Brown.
\par 
\par On this trip Brown found her hut, made of whalebones and a bru
sh roof, and later that day he and the Indians sighted her, watching them from the opposite side of a hill. By the time they reached the spot, however, she had disappeared. From Brown's narrative.
\par 
\par "When we got across to the Indians, I said, 'There's nothi
ng here, let's go back.' There was a basket and. some feathers. She catched shags and had a coat made without sleeves, nicely covered with sealskin. I said to the Indians, 'You go to the hill and scatter the feathers and things in the basket, and if she i
s still alive she will find them.' The same day we fonnd them all gathered up and put in the basket."
\par 
\par Brown resumed the search the next morning and soon caught sight of her tolling up the hill toward the whalebone hut, carrying something heavy in her arms. He describes her capture:
\par 
\par "She had a brush fence, about two feet high, to break the wind, and right in front of me she sat facing me. The sun was coming in her face. She was skinning a seal before I came up to her. Thinking she might run I stepped round 
her, and she bowed as if she knew me before, and when the Indians came up they all kneeled."
\par 
\par After a month on San Nicolas, Capt. Nidever and Brown took the Lost Woman to the Mission of Santa. Barbbara, where she was christened Juana Maria. But the crew of
 Nidever's schocner had already named her "Better Than Nothing" and by that name she was known. She was estimated to have been about forty-five years old when found. All efforts to find Mission Indians who understood her dialect were fruitless and after s
ix weeks at Santa Barbara she became ill and died (--)taking With her the enigma of the disappearance of the Channel Islanders.
\par 
\par San Nicolas' eight miles of lava flows, shifting sand dunes, its 900-foot fog-shrouded peak, its deep cut canyons, its bleak cli
ffs and the crashing seas breaking over its rocky shores make it just about one of the most desolate places on earth.Yet it was one of the most populous of all the islands when Cabrillo and Vizcaino visited the coast and it is still a great treasure groun
d
 for archeologists and souvenir hunters. It is the site of one of the largest aboriginal kitchen middens in the world and here may still be found skulls, pipes, beads, ollas, fiint spear heads and other traces of the ancient island people. San Nicolas is 
literally being blown into the sea and while the northwester iS howling with great force across its desolate expanse one can stand on this bleak desert and see Catalina, where at that same moment an ideal summer climate obtains.
\par 
\par The Santa Barbara Islands
\par 
\par Sailing up channel, the first of the Santa Barbara islands encountered is Anacapa, "the everchanging," in reality three islands of grotesque shape. Anacapa is an island in the last stages of its existence, succumbing to the ravages of wind and sea, and it
s
 shores are therefore formed of myriad caves and arches, where the sea rushes in and out in its never-ceasing effort. The largest of Anacapa's three islets is a peak rising 980 feet above the sea, the whole Anacapa group, in fact, having the appearance of
 a mountain on edge rising out of the sea.
\par 
\par Although less than a hundred miles separate the Santa Barbara islands from the Santa Catalina group a striking change in climate is noted. The westerly wind blows with more gusto down the Santa Barbara Channel and
 its waters seem to be the camp ground of the grim fogs which often envelop the Anacapa Passage. Santa Cruz and Santa Rosa islands, next in order up channel, on the other hand enjoy a salubrious climate, which is like that of Catalina, tempered by a fresh
e
r, cooler west wind. These two islands, both approaching Catalina in size and topographical make-up, are surpassed by none of the Channel group in wild, verdant beauty. Santa Cruz's shores are lined With scores of little coves and bays, there being yachts
m
en and fishermen who Will tell you that Cochies Prietos (--)that perfect little gem of a harbor midway uP the south shore(--)is the prettiest spot on earth. Santa Cruz is world-famous for its great multi-colored shore line caves. Several like the Painted 
C
ave, have sea entrances and open up into cavern-canopied lakes under the mountains, while Cueva Valdez, near the east end, has both shore and sea entrances. The island is owned by the heirs oi Justinian Caire, a Frenchman who a half-century ago establishe
d on its interior valley a beautifUl rancho that is still a faithful reproduction of the vineyard country of Southern France. Sheep are also raised on the Caire rancho, while the island's 
