\par 
\par tree-filled valleys and grassy slopes abound with California valley quail and doves.
\par 
\par Santa Rosa Island, just across the lively Santa Cruz Chanel from Santa Cruz, approaches that isladn in size and natural beauty and contain
s one of the finest cattle ranches in California, maintained jointly by the Vail Company and the J. V. Vickers estate, owners of the island. It is the wild boar hunters' favorite territory and is a winter rendezvous for huge flocks of white geese, which f
e
ed on the upland grazing grounds. Like the other Channel Islands, Snata Rosa is mountainous and cut by deep canyons. Its highest peak, Mount Negro, rises to a height of 1565 feet. Don Carlos and Jose Carrillo, members of the pioneer California family, gai
ned title to Santa Rosa by a grant from teh King of Spain in 1834, from whose hands it later passes to the More brothers, of Santa Barbara, before its purchase by the Vail and Vickers interests.
\par 
\par Cabrillo's Grave
\par 
\par Three miles from Santa Rosa, separated by a
 channel of turbulent waters and dengerous currents, lies San Miguel, wastern sentinel of the entire channel group. Saven and one-half miles long, this desolate, wind-swept island is first seen as twin peaks rising out of the sea. It is government-owned. 
T
reeless and swept continoually by shifting dunes and storms and sand driven by the stron northwester, its shores are for the most part bold and rocky. Cuyler's Harbor, under the lee of Harris Point on the north shore, is the only harbor of value and even 
it is filled with kelp and shoals.
\par 
\par Somewhere along Cuyler's bleak expanse, the remains of Jan Rodriquez Cabrillo are believed to lie, for it was there he died on january 3, 1543, after suffering intensely for two months from the arm he had broken while at 
San Miguel in October. Dying in those lonely, stormy waters fer from home, Cabrillo's valor and courage stayed with him to the last, for Bartolome Ferrelo, his pilot, says in describing his passage:
\par 
\par "He charged them much, at the time of his death, that they would not give up the discovery, as far as possible, of all that coast."
\par 
\par No monument marks his grave, but beneath the shifting sands of San Miguel lies the real discoverer of California. He and Ferrelo did more than all others to increase Spain's king[
d]om in the Pacific, yet the gallant efforts of these two bold sailors are commemorated by not a single prominent landmark along the coast that they were first to find.
